s arise from fundamental beliefs, embedded in the culture, rather than from economic conditions. Identifying the specific values that elsewhere led educators, social activists, religious leaders, trade unionists, military officers, and government bureaucrats to make education compulsory and to end child labor, he explains why similar groups in India do not play the same role.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChild laborxGovernment policyzIndia. 0aChild laborxGovernment policy. 0aChildrenzIndia. 0aEducation, CompulsoryzIndia. 0aEducation, Compulsory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh  aAustria.  aBasic Education.  aConstitution of India.  aEnglish Poor Law (1601).  aEswaran, Girija.  aFactories Act (1948).  aGandhi Labour Institute.  aGandhi, Mahatma.  aGujarat, educational system.  aGupta, Meena.  aHamilton, Alexander.  aHarbans Singh Report.  aHartog Committee.  aIllich, Ivan.  aIndian Educational Services.  aIndian Mines Act (1923).  aIndian National Congress.  aIndian Social Institute.  aInstitute of Education (Pune).  aKarnataka.  aKnights of Labor.  aKnox, John.  aLakshmanan.  aLuther, Martin.  aMassachusetts.  aMines Act (1952).  aOld Deluder Satan Law (1647).  aOperation Blackboard.  aPrema Seva Sadan.  aSmith, Adam.  aapprenticeship.  aattitudes toward childhood.  abidi industry.  abonded labor.  abrassware industry.  acarpet industry.  acommon-school movement.  acottage industries.  adropout rates.  aeducation, state policies.  aexpenditures on education.  afemale education and fertility rates.  afireworks industry.  agoals of education.  aindentured labor.  aliteracy rates.  amatch industry.  aminimum wage.  anonformal education.  apottery industry.  aschool enrollments.  ascience